ichroos is a species of grass in the family Poaceae. It is a perennial herb that typically grows to 50-120 cm in height, with a slender culm and a spread of 30-60 cm. The leaves are linear, flat, and lance-shaped, measuring 20-40 cm in length and 0.3-1.2 cm in width, with a prominent midrib. The panicle is a dense, cylindrical spike with a length of 20-40 cm and a width of 4-6 cm, containing numerous spikelets. The spikelets are bisexual, with a lance-shaped lemma and a hairy, 2-flowered lower floret.", "uses": "Cymbopogon dichroos, also known as East Indian lemon grass, has been traditionally used in various medicinal applications. The essential oils extracted from its leaves have been reported to exhibit anti-inflammatory, antiseptic, and antifungal properties. In traditional medicine, it is used to treat digestive issues, skin irritations, and respiratory problems. The oil's antiseptic properties make it effective in wound healing and preventing infections. Additionally, it has been used as a natural remedy for fever reduction and stress relief.", "taxonomy": "Cymbopogon dichroos is classified as a species of grass in the family Poaceae. It belongs to the genus Cymbopogon and is commonly known as a type of lemongrass. This classification places Cymbopogon dichroos within the larger group of true grasses, which are characterized by their grass-like appearance and growth habit. The family Poaceae is a large and diverse group of plants, including many types of grasses, sedges, and wild rices. Cymbopogon dichroos is a specific and distinct species within this larger group.", "benefits": "Cymbopogon dichroos, commonly known as the Lemon Grass or Citronella Grass, is known for its numerous health benefits. The plant's essential oil has anti-inflammatory properties, which can help alleviate symptoms of arthritis and other inflammatory conditions. The oil also exhibits antimicrobial properties, making it effective in treating skin infections and wounds. Additionally, Cymbopogon dichroos oil has been traditionally used to reduce stress and anxiety due to its calming effects. Its antiseptic properties can also help soothe digestive issues, promoting overall well-being.", "parts": "Cymbopogon dichroos, also known as lemongrass, the medicinal parts of this plant include the leaves, stems, and roots. The essential oils extracted from these parts are used to treat various health issues, such as fever, digestive problems, and stress. The leaves and stems contain citral, a compound with antiseptic and anti-inflammatory properties. The roots of the plant are also used in traditional medicine to treat respiratory problems, such as bronchitis and asthma. These medicinal parts of Cymbopogon dichroos are commonly used in herbal remedies and aromatherapy.", "intro": "Cymbopogon dichroos is a type of grass known for its essential oil, commonly referred to as East Indian lemongrass or Cochin grass. The health benefits of Cymbopogon dichroos include its antimicrobial, anti-inflammatory, and antifungal properties, which make it useful in treating digestive issues, fever, and respiratory problems. The bioactive constituents of Cymbopogon dichroos include limonene, geraniol, and citral, which contribute to its medicinal properties. The most common herbal preparations made from Cymbopogon dichroos include teas, essential oils, and dried leaves, which are often used to make teas, infusions, and aromatherapy products."}